1 AI: commit 3 / H | 1 AI: commit 3 / H / `\"ai_prefix\"` | OK |\n| `story2.txt 4` (`line_A`) | 0 AI checkpoints | commit 1 with 0 checkpoints | OK |\n\nThese all work because `ai_head_1` and `line_A` survive unchanged across commits (just shifted), so `map_new_to_old` returns a valid old line number and the cross-commit trace works. Lines 1 and 3 are created fresh in commit 3 and don't need to trace further back.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n**One bug**: the line-history algorithm doesn't chain backward across commit boundaries when a line was *replaced* (deleted + re-added) within a commit's checkpoints. It needs to: when the earliest checkpoint in a commit *creates* the line but also *deletes* an older version from the previous commit's state, follow that deleted line number into the prior commit and continue the search.",
